ountries with inspiring stories of activism and powerful court cases from around the globe, the book traces the trends in constitution drafting over the past half century and examines how stronger protections against discrimination have transformed lives. Looking at equal rights across gender, race and ethnicity, religion, sexual orientation and gender identity, disability, social class, and migration status, the authors uncover which groups are increasingly guaranteed equal rights in constitutions, whether or not these rights on paper have been translated into practice, and which nations lag behind. Serving as a comprehensive call to action for anyone who cares about their country's future, Advancing Equality challenges us to remember how far we all still must go for equal rights for all. A free open access ebook is available upon publication. Learn more at www.luminosoa.org.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aConstitutional law. 0aEquality before the law. 0aHuman rights. 0aMinoritiesxCivil rights. 0aSocial rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civics & Citizenship.2bisacsh  acomparative analysis of equal rights.  acomprehensive.  aconstitutions of united nations countries.  adisability.  aethnicity.  agender identity.  agender.  ainspiring stories of activism.  amigration status.  apowerful court cases.  aprotections against discrimination.  arace.  areligion.  asexual orientation.  asocial class.  atrends in constitution drafting.1 aRaub, Amy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSprague, Aleta, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBo